{"name":"OWP Productivity Insights","version":"1.4","generated_at":"2026-04-30T03:10:09.275120+00:00","source":"cortex-mockup repo \u00b7 76 cortex output JSONs across 3 schema generations (v2.0/v2.1/v2.2) \u00b7 PROJECT_ORDER 79 closed jobs","cortex_layer":"productivity_insights","audience":"bid_model_calibration","usage_instructions":"Drives the bid intelligence tool calibration panel and the COST_CODES variance defaults. Regenerate via owp/build_calibration.py whenever a new closed job lands.","scope":{"total_jobs":79,"completed_jobs_in_benchmarks":76,"completed_with_unit_data":76,"live_jobs":0,"schemas_loaded":{"xlsx-v2.1":12,"v2.1":16,"v2.0":21,"v2.2":27},"missing_data_jsons":["2016","2020","2026"]},"headline_findings":[{"id":"orig_bid_per_unit_anchor","severity":"critical","title":"Original-bid $/unit clusters tight at $14,978/u (P25 $11,342 \u2013 P75 $18,244)","value":14978.3347,"unit":"USD/unit","summary":"Across 76 closed jobs, the median ORIGINAL contract value per plumbing unit is $14,978. The middle 50% sit between $11,342 and $18,244/unit \u2014 a tight band even across GCs, project sizes, and unit counts. This is the PRIMARY ANCHOR for new-bid calibration. NOTE: this is original (pre-CO) economics, distinct from revenue_per_unit which includes CO traffic.","evidence":{"n":76,"min":2291.0714,"max":24247.9348,"mean":14611.6537,"median":14978.3347,"p25":11341.8954,"p50":14978.3347,"p75":18243.5487,"p10":8726.6533,"p90":19828.6238,"note":"Original contract value / plumbing units (PRIMARY ANCHOR for new-bid calibration \u2014 pre-CO)","unit":"USD"},"implication":"Use orig_bid_per_unit as the FIRST calibration step for any new bid. $/fixture is a poor anchor when fixture density varies between project types (small studios 4 fx/u vs full apartments 7-8 fx/u). $/unit is durable across density. Then add scope-specific premiums per-unit (heat-pump central plant: ~$2,100/u; below-grade garage drainage: ~$400/u; dense-urban site complexity: ~$600/u) calibrated against comp-to-comp deltas, NOT generic percentage cushions."},{"id":"orig_vs_final_distinction","severity":"critical","title":"CO traffic median is +2.7% \u2014 original bid \u2260 final billed","value":0.0272,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median (final - original) / original = +2.7%. The bid tool MUST distinguish original-bid economics (for calibrating new bids) from final-billed economics (for retrospective margin analysis). Calibrating new bids against final $/u biases UPWARD \u2014 the additional CO traffic isn't part of a fresh bid scope.","evidence":{"n":16,"min":-0.099,"max":0.1222,"mean":0.0289,"median":0.0272,"p25":0.0142,"p50":0.0272,"p75":0.0644,"p10":-0.0288,"p90":0.0845,"note":"(Final - Original) / Original \u2014 CO traffic posture by job","unit":"fraction"},"implication":"Bid-tool dropdowns and calibration anchors should default to ORIGINAL contract values. Final values belong in margin/CO-pattern analysis, not in scope pricing."},{"id":"material_takeoff_systematically_conservative","severity":"high","title":"OWP material takeoffs systematically come in under original budget","value":-0.2762,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 76 completed jobs, the median material variance from original budget to actual spend is -27.6%. Negative means UNDER budget. This is the strongest single signal in the dataset for calibrating the bid model.","evidence":{"n_jobs":571,"p25":-0.4942,"median":-0.2762,"p75":-0.0545},"implication":"Two valid responses for the bid model: (a) tighten the takeoff factor by ~25% and bid a leaner number, or (b) hold the cushion as a declared margin contribution and report it explicitly to leadership. Without an explicit policy, this cushion compounds opaquely."},{"id":"roughin_labor_overruns","severity":"high","title":"Rough-in labor (code 120) is the major labor code that runs over budget","value":0.1382,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Across 76 completed jobs, code 120 (rough-in labor) has a median original\u2192actual variance of +13.8%. Most other major labor codes run UNDER budget. This means takeoff hours for rough-in are systematically too low.","evidence":{"code":"120","description":"Roughin Labor","n_jobs":76,"variance_orig_to_actual":{"n":76,"min":-0.4403,"max":1.2339,"mean":0.1448,"median":0.1382,"p25":-0.0712,"p50":0.1382,"p75":0.2684,"p10":-0.1916,"p90":0.5261},"median_actual_dollars":229943.99},"implication":"Bid model should apply a +10\u201315% correction factor to rough-in labor takeoff specifically. Material cushion alone does not compensate for this \u2014 labor is harder to recover once underbid."},{"id":"hours_per_unit_house_standard","severity":"high","title":"House standard for labor productivity is ~117 hours per plumbing unit","value":117.4259,"unit":"hours","summary":"Median is 117.4 hrs/unit (P25 100, P75 144). The middle 50% of jobs sit between 100 and 144 hrs/unit \u2014 that is the credible band for a like-for-like new bid.","evidence":{"n":76,"min":49.5119,"max":363.4877,"mean":129.9373,"median":117.4259,"p25":100.1388,"p50":117.4259,"p75":143.6848,"p10":79.3665,"p90":184.1038,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"implication":"Bids that fall below P25 or above P75 should be flagged for explicit justification \u2014 the bidding tool should not silently extrapolate beyond the historical band."},{"id":"gross_margin_band","severity":"medium","title":"Gross margin clusters at 38.4%","value":0.384,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Median gross margin is 38.4%. This is what OWP earns once direct cost (labor + material + burden + tax) is removed from billed revenue.","evidence":{"n_jobs":76,"p25":0.311,"median":0.384,"p75":0.4539},"implication":"Use as default target margin. Combine with material-takeoff cushion finding for total margin posture."},{"id":"wage_burden","severity":"medium","title":"Fully loaded labor cost is ~$40.97/hr (1.42\u00d7 blended)","value":40.9712,"unit":"USD/hr","summary":"Median fully loaded wage (labor + burden) is $40.97/hr. Burden multiplier of 1.42\u00d7 means OWP carries ~42% on top of direct wages for taxes, insurance, vehicles, etc.","evidence":{"blended_wage_median":28.5923,"loaded_wage_median":40.9712,"burden_multiplier_median":1.4248},"implication":"Always price labor at fully-loaded wage in the bid model."},{"id":"labor_variance_neutral","severity":"medium","title":"Labor variance is roughly balanced (-16.3% median)","value":-0.163,"unit":"fraction","summary":"Unlike material (consistently under), labor variance from original budget to actual is closer to neutral (median -16.3%). The bid model should NOT assume a labor cushion the way it can for material.","evidence":{"n":722,"min":-0.9914,"max":4.6293,"mean":-0.1043,"median":-0.163,"p25":-0.4268,"p50":-0.163,"p75":0.1183,"p10":-0.618,"p90":0.434},"implication":"Bid the labor number close to the takeoff \u2014 there is no systematic safety margin."}],"benchmarks":{"hours_per_unit":{"n":76,"min":49.5119,"max":363.4877,"mean":129.9373,"median":117.4259,"p25":100.1388,"p50":117.4259,"p75":143.6848,"p10":79.3665,"p90":184.1038,"note":"Total field hours / plumbing units","unit":"hours"},"labor_dollars_per_unit":{"n":76,"min":359.0298,"max":5959.7848,"mean":3314.995,"median":3490.6273,"p25":2525.5148,"p50":3490.6273,"p75":4082.3873,"p10":1708.6306,"p90":4705.8303,"note":"Direct labor cost / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"material_dollars_per_unit":{"n":76,"min":899.1928,"max":6832.3193,"mean":3554.6572,"median":3403.2433,"p25":2802.5368,"p50":3403.2433,"p75":4258.8443,"p10":2061.6333,"p90":5080.1645,"note":"200-series cost code spend / plumbing units","unit":"USD"},"revenue_per_unit":{"n":76,"min":2291.0714,"max":24733.087,"mean":14691.7271,"median":15493.5369,"p25":11475.4723,"p50":15493.5369,"p75":18130.7228,"p10":8726.6533,"p90":19828.6238,"note":"999 sales code billed / plumbing units (FINAL \u2014 includes CO traffic)","unit":"USD"},"orig_bid_per_unit":{"n":76,"min":2291.0714,"max":24247.9348,"mean":14611.6537,"median":14978.3347,"p25":113